'''Sir David John Watson''' (22 March 1949{{spaced ndash}}8 February 2015) was a British academic and [[educationalist]]. He was Director of [[Brighton Polytechnic]] from 1990 to 1992 and [[Vice-Chancellor]] of its successor the [[University of Brighton]] from 1992 to 2005. He was the [[Principal (academia)|Principal]] of [[Green Templeton College, Oxford]] and Professor of Higher Education at the [[University of Oxford]] from 2010 to 2015.

==Early life==
Watson was born on 22 March 1949 in [[Broxbourne]], England.<ref name="IoE - CV" /> He was educated at [[Cheshunt School]], then a [[grammar school]] in Cheshunt, Hertfordshire, before winning a Fleming Scholarship to attend [[Eton College]].<ref name="IoE - CV" /><ref name="obit - University of Sussex" /> In 1968, he [[matriculated]] into [[Clare College, Cambridge]], where he was a [[choral scholar]] and studied history. He graduated with a [[first class honours|first class]] [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) degree.<ref name="obit - Clare Alumni">{{cite web|title=Sir David Watson (1968)|url=http://www.clarealumni.com/s/845/1col.aspx?sid=845&gid=1&pgid=252&cid=2989&ecid=2989&ciid=10358&crid=0|website=Clare Alumni|publisher=Clare College, Cambridge|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> As a [[Thouron Award|Thouron Scholar]], he attended the [[University of Pennsylvania]], from which he graduated with a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (PhD) degree in [[intellectual history]] in 1975.<ref name="obit - Oxford Brookes University">{{cite web|title=Tribute to Sir David Watson|url=http://www.brookes.ac.uk/about-brookes/news/tribute-to-sir-david-watson/|website=News|publisher=Oxford Brookes University|accessdate=16 February 2015|date=12 February 2015}}</ref>

==Career==
From 1981 to 1990, he was [[Dean (education)|Dean]] and Deputy Director of [[Oxford Brookes University|Oxford Polytechnic]].<ref name="obit - University of Sussex">{{cite web|title=Obituary: Sir David Watson|url=http://www.sussex.ac.uk/broadcast/read/29016|website=Broadcast|publisher=University of Sussex|accessdate=16 February 2015|date=10 February 2015}}</ref> In 1990, he was appointed Director of [[Brighton Polytechnic]]. In 1992, Brighton Polytechnic was [[Further and Higher Education Act 1992|granted university status]]. He continued as its head and was appointed the first [[Vice-Chancellor]] of the [[University of Brighton]].<ref name="Brighton uni - Vice-Chancellor to step down at the university">{{cite web|title=Vice-Chancellor to step down at the university|url=http://www.brighton.ac.uk/news/2004/040720watson.php?PageId=824|publisher=University of Brighton|accessdate=25 April 2014|date=20 June 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426201633/http://www.brighton.ac.uk/news/2004/040720watson.php?PageId=824|archive-date=26 April 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref> In 2005, he joined the [[Institute of Education]], then part of [[University of London]], as Professor of Higher Education and Co-Director of its Centre for Higher Education Studies.<ref name="IoE - CV" /><ref name="The Argus - Tributes paid to academic who helped to create University of Brighton">{{cite news|last1=Vowles|first1=Neil|title=Tributes paid to academic who helped to create University of Brighton|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/11781970.Tributes_paid_to_academic_who_helped_to_create_University_of_Brighton/|accessdate=10 February 2015|work=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]]|date=10 February 2015}}</ref>

He was a Trustee of the [[Nuffield Foundation]] from 2005 to 2015.<ref>http://www.nuffieldfoundation.org/past-trustees-and-directors</ref>

In 2010, he was elected of [[Principal (academia)|Principal]] of [[Green Templeton College, Oxford]].<ref name="Green Templeton - Professor Sir David Watson to head Green Templeton College">{{cite web|title=Professor Sir David Watson to head Green Templeton College|url=http://www.gtc.ox.ac.uk/news-and-views/news-articles/archive/558-professor-sir-david-watson-to-head-green-templeton-college.html|work=News|publisher=Green Templeton College, Oxford|accessdate=25 April 2014|date=16 December 2009}}</ref> Upon taking up the position, he was also appointed Professor of Higher Education at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name="bio - Department of Education, University of Oxford">{{cite web|title=Professor Sir David Watson|url=http://www.education.ox.ac.uk/about-us/directory/professor-sir-david-watson/|work=People|publisher=Department of Education, University of Oxford|accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref>

He was a member of the [[National Committee of Inquiry into Higher Education]] (commonly known as the Dearing Review) which published a highly influential report, ''Higher Education in the Learning Society'', in 1997. It made a large number of recommendations to improve higher education in the UK, including the introduction of [[tuition fees]]. He was chairman of the Inquiry into the Future for Lifelong Learning and co-authored its report, ''Learning Through Life'', which was published in 2009.<ref name="obit - THE" />

==Honours and awards==
Watson was awarded a knighthood in 1998 for services to higher education. In 2009 he was given the ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' [[Lord Dearing]] Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref name="obit - THE"/> He was also the recipient of eight Honorary Doctorates in addition to Honorary Fellowships of [[Queen Mary University of London]] and the City and Guilds Institute London, and Honorary Membership of the [[Royal College of Music]].<ref name="Department of Education, University of Oxford obit">{{cite web | title= Professor Sir David Watson |url=  http://www.education.ox.ac.uk/about-us/directory/professor-sir-david-watson/| | author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| website= www.education.ox.ac.uk | accessdate= 23 February 2015}}</ref>

Following his death, the University of Brighton announced its intention to name a new academic building and library in his honour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tributes to Professor Sir David Watson|url=https://www.brighton.ac.uk/about-us/news-and-events/news/2015/02-09_tributes-to-professor-sir-david-watson.aspx|website=University of Brighton|publisher=University of Brighton|accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref><ref name="Times Higher Education 12 February 2015">{{cite web | title= Colleagues pay tribute to Sir David Watson’s career|url=  http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/colleagues-pay-tribute-to-sir-david-watsons-career/2018489.article| first= Jack| last= Grove| date= 12 February 2015 | website= www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/ | accessdate= 23 February 2015}}</ref> The Watson building was rededicated in September 2018.<ref name="Watson Building">{{cite web|url=https://www.brighton.ac.uk/about-us/news-and-events/news/2018/09-20-watson-building-dedicated-in-memory-of-former-vice-chancellor.aspx|title=Watson Building dedicated in memory of former Vice-Chancellor|publisher=brighton.ac.uk|accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref>

==Death==
Watson died on 8 February 2015, shortly after being diagnosed with cancer.<ref name="Times Higher Education 12 February 2015"/> He was aged 65.<ref name="obit - THE">{{cite news|last1=Parr|first1=Chris|title=Sir David Watson dies aged 65|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/sir-david-watson-dies-aged-65/2018425.article|accessdate=10 February 2015|work=Times Higher Education|date=9 February 2015}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Watson was married to Betty Pinto Skolnick. He had a keen interest in music and was an accomplished pianist; together with his wife he regularly hosted informal music evenings at Green Templeton College for its amateur musicians. He also contributed to the development of more formal musical and artistic events for the College’s social calendar.<ref name="obit – Green Templeton College">{{cite web | title= Professor Sir David Watson 1949-2015 |url= http://www.gtc.ox.ac.uk/news-and-views/news-articles/1251-professor-sir-david-watson-1949-2015.html| author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| website= www.gtc.ox.ac.uk | accessdate= 23 February 2015}}</ref>  He and his wife had two children, Michael and Sarah, born in 1980 and 1984.<ref name="IoE - CV">{{cite web|title=CV - Professor Sir David Watson|url=http://www.ioe.ac.uk/about/documents/DW_short_cv_22.10.09.pdf|publisher=Institute of Education|accessdate=10 February 2015|format=pdf|date=22 October 2009}}</ref>

==Selected works==
Watson was a prolific author; in addition to his own books and those which he edited and co-authored, he also published some 400 monographs and pamphlets, chapters in books, articles and reviews.<ref name="IoE - CV" />

*{{cite book|last1=Bines|first1=Hazel|last2=Watson|first2=David|title=Developing professional education: a polytechnic perspective|date=1992|publisher=Society for Research into Higher Education / Open University Press|location=Milton Keynes|isbn=0335097103}}
* {{cite book| author = David Watson | title = Managing Civic and Community Engagement | date = 1 April 2007| publisher = Open University Press | isbn= 978-0335220472}}
* {{cite book| author = David Watson | title = The Question of Morale: Searching for Happiness in University Life | date = 1 October 2009| publisher = Open University Press | isbn= 978-0335235605}}
*{{cite book|last1=Schuller|first1=Tom|last2=Watson|first2=David|title=Learning through life: inquiry into the future for lifelong learning|date=2009|publisher=National Institute of Adult Continuing Education|location=Leicester|isbn=1862014337}}
* {{cite book| author1 = David Watson | author2= Robert Hollister |author3= Susan E. Stroud | author4= Elizabeth Babcock |title = The Engaged University: International Perspectives on Civic Engagement (International Studies in Higher Education)| date = 15 February 2013 | publisher = Routledge | isbn= 978-0415824224}}
* {{cite book| author = David Watson | title = The Question of Conscience: Higher education and personal responsibility | date = 1 December 2013| publisher = Institute of Education Press | isbn= 978-1782770268}}

